beer_brewer_name: Port Brewing Co / The Lost Abbey
review_blob: Gold to bronze in color with a decent head. The aroma exudes piny and oily hop resins with wet, bitter leafyness and soaked in co-humulones. A nice summer, humid spicyness lurks around the bouquet. Juicy body, full of spicy and piny hops. Nice leafyness and some moderate to high co-humulones. Spicy grapefruit and spicy lemon zest finish. An IPA that really delivers a punch.
beer_name: The Hop Concept Galaxy & Comet IPA

review_blob: Ginger-ale colored, highly carbonated, and with a creamy head. Nice leafy aroma with gentle cohumlones. The flavor is similar, with nice bitter pinyness, leafyness, co-humlone, and perhaps some herbal and spicy hop notes across an easy-going malt background. Quite sessionable.

Chestnut brown with a mahogany underpinning and a burnt orange-tannish cream head. The bouquet releases notes of fig sugar accompanied by muted phenols to create an enjoyable aromatic platform. Dark caramel raisin, some prune, and alcohol raisin notes soon arise. The body is well apportioned with prune and dark Belgian sugar, and perhaps some India palm sugar/jaggery contributing some interesting sweetness. Just a soupcon of gum. Cherry-raisin notes on the finish. Excellent mouthfeel, complex, and well-rounded, with rich, dark esters. Wonderful.
Bronze body with a ring of lace. Nice farmhousey, wild and sour wheat nose. Blonde grain with a nice rind of vanilla wild yeastiness. Tart caramel grain finish. Tasty and refreshing.

Bronzed body with a thin, faded head. Bitter, thin leafy hop nose. On the palate, this one reflects English-style craftmanship with some bitter leafy hops with notes of tea. Watered sugar finish. A decent change of pace the straddles the EPA / ESB styles, more than an IPA.

Sasparilla to black colored, with a decent enough head. The aroma is sooty roastiness with a burnt charcoal character. The body too was quite roasty with some acrid and sooty touches. Medium-bodied. Ok, but lacking in complexity.

Hazy tannish wheat color. The aroma is of crackled wheat and the Earth. Earthy wheat and somewhat tart flavor. Perhaps the slightest trace of coriander, but its a real small factor. A satisfying, refreshing brew that tastes of wholesome ingredients.
Crystal blonde with a thin head. Earthy, crackled grain aroma with a slight breadiness. Easy beery and yeasty body with no detectable phenols. Moderate body though perhaps slightly watery.

Golden blonde, decent head. Moderate co-humulone nose with a bouquet that is quite approachable. Nice leafy, bitter body with moderate co-humulone. Nice 2-row malt backbone balances out the sharp bitterness. Really solid.

Black body, think chocolate filmy head. Dense roasty nose is reluctant to unfurl. The body provides and experience of smooth rolled oats across the palate accented by dark chocolate and roast barley notes that are tightly coiled together. Robust and ever so drinkable.
Amber body, lightly browned head. This one emanates a caramel malted nose that leads to a body has strong toffeeish and caramel malt notes. Sticky hops with a touch of cotton candy.
beer_name: Knee Deep McCarthys Bane Imperial Red Ale

review_blob: Sasparilla body with a caramel-brown head. Pumpkin pie spiced nose and body. The spicing definitely veers toward all spiced. A modest roast barley backbone supports the spicing with coffee notes. Slightly sweet.

Copper colored with a nice frothy head renewed by streams of carbonation. The body starts off rather dank, but after aeration, it blows forth a profusion of esters and stone fruits, such as strawberry essence, with some stale bread crust in the background. A yeast saturated body replete with esters, some bread crust, and stone fruit. A liquid yeast and sourdough finish, with notes of unripe banana skin and apple.. Definitely improves with aeration and warming.

Hazy tan and golden grain body. Aroma of hay and barley with a nice estery yeastyness to it. Full-bodied, rounded out by hay, barley, and oat notes in a swirl of rich yeasty esters. Redolent of fields of grain and bountiful farmland. Earthy, filling, and satisfying.
Orange-amber body with a nice head. Easy flowing citrus aroma. The body is softly grainy, but also characterized by a grittyiness. Citrusy hops wash over the palate and linger.

Black-bodied with a decent enough cocoa head. Full-bodied aroma, hearty coffee with some doses of chocolate and a nice complexity of spicier notes and smoke. Medium to full-bodied on the palate, yet quaffable. Nice complexity of coffee roast, chocolate, easy-going smokyness, and perhaps a touch of anise. Solid
Bronzed body, decent head. Moderately citrusy aroma with a touch of spicyness and hop leaf. Citrusy hops on the palate with a decent leafy bitterness with some greenness to it.

Bronze body with lively carbonation feeding a full, beige head. Aromatically, this one is gently sweet and clean with some leafy floral notes joined by a grapefruit note and a touch of pine. Nice. The flavor is consistent with the aroma, though perhaps somewhat sweeter and less bitter than I would prefer. Pineapple grapefruit splash finish.
Woody amber mahogany body, with an ok head. Not much aroma, but the body is sugary and characterized by watered down esters accompanied by candi malt.

This fruit saison was a watery brass color with a slight head and big soda bubbles of carbonation. As advertised this brew has a jammy raspberry nose. Similarly, the body is saturated with jammy fruit, most notably raspberry. Its definitely a tasty fruit beer, but not remotely saison-like.
Crystal bronze-gold body with a nice silky head. The aroma is of feint hoppyness. The body is of a soft floral hop quality with a touch of rosewater.

Bronzed and hazyish with a ring of head. Nice graininess in the nose, accompanied by slight toastiness. Light body with an easy, warming current of grainy toastyness, rounded out by a touch of tannins. This is a light-weight, crisp, grain-forward brew.

Golden bodied, with good carbonation feeding just a wispy ring of head. Easy bready graininess in the nose. Clean bouquet with no discernable hops. On the palate, this one is bready and more filling that the appearance would suggest. Restrained tannins with a touch of greenness at the end of the palate. Grassy hops. Again, well-crafted for what it is--a pilsner.

Bronze body, dense, slightly off-white, head, and good carbonation. Bouquet discharges clean, floral bitterness that seems Centennial-forward. Simple, unadorned leafyness. Likewise the body tastes of hop leafyness, a touch green and herbal. Powdery hop finish. Well-crafted for what it is--a session-style IPA, but rather thin and lacking in complexity.

Peach-amber colored body topped by a poofy, airy thick head. Estery and yeasty nose with spritzes of soapyness and a touch of banana and clove. Earthy grain body with overlays of bread, clove, and banana. Lively, effervescent yeastiness.

Luminous orange-bronze with fluff-cream thick off-white head. Deliciously floral leafy nose with honeyed hop notes. A pleasant foresty hop spicyness to the aroma. The flavor is juicy pine--quite piquant and with appreciable foresty spicyness. Prickly pine juice and grapefruit hop finish. A lovely pine-forward IPA.

Bronzish-orange body topped by a lacey, silky white head. Yeasty, bready, estery, and phenolic nose with a strong dose of banana and a touch of clove. Again, lively esters on the pate. The taste of liquid yeast envelops the palate. Buzzy quality on the tongue. Some twangy sourness, wheat, and muted phenols.

The color of ancient amber with a thick frothy and lacy head. Wonderfully zesty bready and wheaty nose with licks of banana. Sweet and green banana flavors with some funky esters, and wheat bread. The flavors are a bit uneven--perhaps this would mellow a bit with additional aging. Not bad by any means, just a bit jarring with some of the rough edges.

Golden bodied, well carbonated, and topped with a full head of froth. This brew smells clean, floral, and slightly foresty, amidst a silent, pale malt backbone. The body lands with bitterish, watery leafy notes on the palate. Light 2-row backbone provides a clean graininess.
beer_name: Catalina Island Casino Royale Pale Ale

review_blob: Hazy tan-yellow brew with a thin head. Gently tart wheat nose. Intensely sprucy body. Juicy and prickly mouthfeel. Sweet flavors roll over the tongue, with perhaps a touch of vanilla. Nice in small doses. A decent spruce ale.

Deep mahogany body with a nice burnt beige cream layered of head. Thick cinnamon nose with some allspice and nutmeg wound in. Again, cinnamon dominates the flavor, and is joined by nutmeg and allspice, all massaged across smooth, black malts. Overall, a bit too heavy-handed on the spicing.

Dark brown-black chocolate body, not much head. Robust malt ball chocolate ovaltine aroma and a similarly ovaltine body with a lactose quality. Bittersweet chocolate syrup waves lead up to a clashing bitter hop finish. This beer has some nice flavor attributes, but in the end, they dont quite mesh well together.
beer_name: Catalina Island Dancing Goat Harbor Coffee Porter

review_blob: Sunrise color with a wheaty chaff head. Sharply bitter citrusy nose. The body is acerbically hoppy,, with a catty citrus smash. Screwdriver finish.

Bronzed body with luscious, off-white head. Appealing Chinook-Centennial hop bouquet, full of leafy bitterness. Floral hop body with more fruitiness than expected. Medium bitterness. Bitter-sweet, fruity finish.

This one pours a vibrant amber body with a rocky, beige head. Herbal and blueberry bouquet with just an intimation of vanilla. Tea-like aroma. The body is of blueberry and vanilla with an ESB-like herbal hop bitterness. Herbal blueberry finish with mild bitterness and sweetness.

Bronzed body with a 1/2" thick head. Mild, leafy bitter nose with a touch of citrus. The body exhibits qualities that are reflective of the flavor along with more of an orange zest presence. Nicely balanced and refreshing.
Amber bodied with a decent head. Characterized by a distinct fruity, peach-forward aroma and flavor. Mild floral bitterness throughout. An amiable APA.

A glass full of sunrise with a decent froth on top. Initially, the aroma and flavor are characterized with citrus and wheat notes. Eventually, banana notes appear and grow prominent. Full-bodied. Solid.

Bronzed body with a full, off-white head. Nose of bread, some cloudy ester notes, and clovey-smoke phenols. Fullness to the body. Bready character spiced up with clove and a touch of banana phenol notes. Fairly simple, but enjoyable.

Bronze body, full rocky head. Amber malt aroma with some bitter Chinook-like notes. Similarly, the body is of moderate amber malts and moderately bitter Chinook-like hops with some pinyness to it. Peachy fruitiness on the finish.

Tan bodied with a decent head. Profuse catty nose accompanied amidst a heavy, humid summers night aroma. The body is drastically more appealing with a dense hoppyness that includes some evergreen and tropical fruit notes. Bitter, humid summer, co-humulone presence fills the mouth. Enjoyable.

Hazy tan body, with an okay head. Nice yeasty nose with some lemon, bready, clovey phenols, and just a hint of pepperiness. The body starts off similarly, tasting of liquid bread yeast, with some lemon and sage notes, joined by predominantly clovey phenols and a touch of pepper. After 5-10 min of aeration, banana phenols grow more pronounced and soon dominate the flavor. A bit of soap on the finish.

I would consider this more of a fruit / herb / vegetable beer than a kolsch. Carnelian body with an ok head. The nose is an interesting punchy fruit and herbal mix. The body actually has a prickly quality to it that burns the end of the tongue. Punchy and botanical infused notes define this brew. Definitely something a little bit different.

Darkish amber body with a resilient tan head. Moderate fruity and tannic aroma. The body is characterized my fruity hoppiness accompanied tannic amber graininess with a touch of shoe. The grain combinations arent quite able to mesh harmoniously. Inoffensive, but forgettable.
beer_name: Uncle Bears Dog Park Dark Ale

review_blob: Maroon-amber body with little carbonation. Spicy gum drop nose with some clovey and candi malt notes and a breeze of wheat. The body strikes a similar chord with some clovey phenol and candi malt notes distinctly present along with a light vein of wheatiness. Notes of cherry cough syrup arise as well.
Brownish orange-amber, ok head. Fruity alcohol nose, and a similar flavor. Some tropical fruits and a touch of smooth brown malt. High-octane feel to it. Citrusy and pineapple finish.

Crystal blonde, well-carbonated, and with a decent, creamy wheaty head. Leafy hoppy with some greenness to it and light, fresh-milled grain nose. Watery grain body with muted hoppyness and some green notes. Sourdough and mild tannin grain finish.

Highly carbonated golden-tan bodied beer, ok head. Grassy, thick summer fields of grass and weeds saturates the nose. So too, the body is highly grassy in character punctuated by some floral notes, pollen, and a thicket of weeds blown about in warm summer air. Coriander notes eventually arise in both aroma and flavor.
Bronze amber with a light think cream tan head. Nice woody juniper / gin botanical perfumed nose. The body is also characterized by a botanical perfumey gin flavor, like an Old Tom gin.
beer_name: North Sound Gin Juniper Pale Ale

review_blob: Golden grain colored body with a thin, airy head. Nice heavy herbal, earthy, and floral hop note with perhaps a trace of tropical fruit. Leafy hop flavor with some grassy and tropical overtones. Body is on the thin side for an IPA. Solid overall.
